description:
secretx-core/src/lib.rs:330,348: 'let hex: String = chars.by_ref().take(4).collect();' allocates a heap String to hold 4 ASCII hex digits, just to feed it to u32::from_str_radix. Same pattern at line 348 for the low surrogate.

Two issues:
1. Allocation per \uXXXX escape — for a long secret value full of escapes (uncommon but plausible) this is real overhead.
2. The hex digits live in non-Zeroizing heap memory, however briefly. Not a serious leak (4 bytes per escape) but inconsistent with the crate's 'don't put secret material in unzeroed buffers' design intent.

Fix: build the u32 directly from chars without an intermediate String:
    let mut code = 0u32;
    for _ in 0..4 {
        let c = chars.next().ok_or(...)?;
        let d = c.to_digit(16).ok_or(...)? ;
        code = (code << 4) | d;
    }
This is also more clearly correct than parsing a string and then validating its length.
